My project is called Temperature Converter. It’s a simple Python program that asks the user 
to type a temperature in Celsius. The input is converted into a number using float(), 
so the program can perform calculations.

Then, it applies the standard formula (Celsius * 9/5) + 32 to 
find the equivalent in Fahrenheit. Finally, it prints both values clearly: 
the Celsius entered and the Fahrenheit result.

What makes this script useful is that it’s interactive. 
Instead of hardcoding numbers, the user can enter any value, and the program instantly provides the conversion. 
In just a few lines of code, we automate a real-world calculation and show how Python handles input, variables, and arithmetic.